Scale up
========

A user wants to access the website www.foobar.com from a browser.

1. The user types https://www.foobar.com in the browser.
2. The browser asks DNS to translate www.foobar.com into an IP address.
3. The DNS zone for foobar.com has a www record that points to the public
   virtual IP address shared by the HAproxy load balancer cluster.
4. One of the HAproxy load balancers receives the request.
5. The load balancer forwards the request to the web server layer.
6. The Nginx web server receives the HTTP or HTTPS request.
7. If the request is for static content, Nginx can serve it directly.
8. If the request needs dynamic content, Nginx forwards it to the application
   server.
9. The application server runs the application code from the application files.
10. If data is needed, the application server queries the database server.
11. The response travels back from the application server to Nginx, then to the
    load balancer, then to the user's browser.

Infrastructure
--------------

Load balancer 1:

    Components:
        - HAproxy

Load balancer 2:

    Components:
        - HAproxy configured in a cluster with Load balancer 1

Server 1:

    Role:
        - Web server

    Components:
        - Nginx

Server 2:

    Role:
        - Application server

    Components:
        - Application server
        - Application files, which are the website code base

Server 3:

    Role:
        - Database server

    Components:
        - MySQL database

Why each additional element is added
------------------------------------

The additional server is added so the infrastructure can split the web server,
application server, and database into separate machines. This makes the design
cleaner and easier to scale because each server has a dedicated role.

The second HAproxy load balancer is added to remove the load balancer as a
single point of failure. If one load balancer fails, the other load balancer can
continue accepting traffic.

The HAproxy cluster is added so both load balancers work together. They can be
configured with a shared virtual IP address using a failover tool such as
Keepalived. In that setup, one HAproxy node owns the virtual IP address, and the
other can take over if the first one fails.

The dedicated web server is added to handle the HTTP layer. Nginx receives user
requests, serves static files, handles web-specific configuration, and forwards
dynamic requests to the application server.

The dedicated application server is added to run the application logic
separately from the web server and database. This makes it easier to deploy
application code, tune application resources, and scale application processing
without directly changing the database server.

The dedicated database server is added to store persistent data separately from
the web and application layers. Databases usually need different resources and
tuning, especially disk performance, memory, backups, and replication.

Why splitting components helps
------------------------------

Splitting the web server, application server, and database onto their own
servers makes the infrastructure easier to scale and maintain.

If the website receives more static or HTTP traffic, more web servers can be
added behind the load balancer.

If the application logic becomes slow, more application servers can be added or
the application server can be given more CPU and memory.

If the database becomes the bottleneck, the database layer can be optimized,
replicated, backed up, or scaled without mixing those changes with the web and
application layers.

This separation also reduces resource competition. Nginx, the application
server, and MySQL no longer fight for the same CPU, memory, disk, and network
resources on a single machine.
